You can login using `$browser-&gt;loginAs($user)`, but you will have to create the user before of course.

What might also be necessary, and I remember fiddling around with that for a long time myself as well, is to commit your database changes before running the test code (i.e. `$this-&gt;browse(...)`). This is because of the way a Dusk test is performed. Normal unit tests are all performed in the same process, which uses the same connection and has therefore the same state. A Dusk test is performed using multiple processes, one is like a unit test and one emulates the browser. Therefore changes to a database need to be committed, which does normally happen implicitly when closing a connection (at least for SQLite databases).

The following, very basic test should give you a direction:

    public function test_home_screen_is_accessible_by_authentication_user(): void
    {
        /** @var User $user */
        $user = factory(User::class)-&gt;state(&#39;dusk&#39;)-&gt;create();
        DB::commit();

        $this-&gt;browse(function (Browser $browser) use ($user) {
            $browser-&gt;loginAs($user)
                -&gt;visit(new HomePage);
        });
